column168: XPO Logistics terminal LHO experienced a release from a 5-gallon poly pail due to a puncture caused by improper dunnage. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 3-gallons of product released to 3' x 4' area of the trailer floor & a 3' x 3' area of the asphalt lot below due to a puncture. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The damaged pail & cleanup debris were then placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On April 3, 2023, at 1015 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar Ranger personnel in Alachua, Florida regarding the release of approximately 1 gallon of Eco-San (Hypochlorite solutions, UN1791 8, III) and approximately 8 gallons of Ultra-San (Hypochlorite solutions, UN1791 8, III).  The releases were reportedly due to leaks in the product containers.  The release was contained to the trailer floor.  Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE.  The released products, spent absorbents and all other waste generated were containerized in (3) 55-gallon poly drums.  The waste drums were then transported off site for proper disposal.

column168: XPO Logistics Terminal XAY experienced a UN2428 "RE/GEN CC-45" release from a 30-gallon poly drum due to improper packaging. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. column168: Around 5pm central time I received a call from Toby Owens who works for Bozeman. Toby told me he was fueling up at the Loves at 335 LA-594, Monroe, LA, 71203 and was doing a walk around of set and noticed a pool of paint (UN1263, Paint, 3, PGIII) on ground and that it was still leaking from his rear pup (287281F). Toby notified central dispatch and they told him to contact Billy or myself. I contacted Hazmat One at 524pm and told them to make all the necessary phone calls and to take all waste with them. Toby mentioned it started to rain and Loves Truck Stop helped contain the spill from spreading more. Hazmat One arrived at Loves at 835pm to start cleaning spill. Hazmat One is renting a boom to unload trailer to clean up. They believe the leak is coming from a drum in nose of trailer. They projected a time of 600am to have spill cleaned up. Release was caused by a nail in the pallet the drums were loaded on. The nail during transit had punctured a hole in the bottom on one drum. Majority of material had leaked into the trailer
column169: Shipper will be notified of incident and that it could have been prevented with a better inspection of pallet.

column168: A tote of UN1866 has been damaged by an 086 forklift blade when the tote was being repositioned on the 086 dock.  The tote had a leak out the top of the tote when the tote is positioned on its side to move the puncture hole (1.5 inches) to the top side of the tote.  086 is attempted to fill the punc ture hole with shrinkwrap to stop the leak in the side of the tote.  The tote was to be positioned in a tilted position to prevent leaking out the top bung on the tote and the puncture hole on the side of the tote.  The plastic shrinkwrap that is being used to plug the puncture hole in the side of t he tote has slowed the spill from the puncture hole to a steady drip.  086 requested an immediate call for a HM cleanup team. ~~HazMat Spill Response Crew was dispatched to the location.~~NOTE: 086 had a tote from 04/06/2023, on the same shipment, that was leaking around the duct tape patch job done  by the spill team from 04/06/2023.  This leak is a slow drip.~~Summary: At this time on the 086 dock we have the tote from yesterday (4-6-23, Thursday) that is still dripping out the spill team cleanup.  The second leaking tote is dripping out the puncture hole from Friday, 4-7-23.  086 is requeste d animmediate call to a HM cleanup team for both leaking totes located on the 086 dock.  086 is using staydry to control the slow spillage coming from both totes.

column168: Poly 275 gal tote fell from the forks while attempting to be placed on top of another tote.  The poly tote burst and the contents released onto the warehouse floor.    The cause was from the bottom of top tote catching the bottom tote metal cage while repositioning.  The tote was caught and when top tote (that fell) was raised, the brought up the bottom tote.  Then the bottom tote fell and broke the bottom of top tote's pallet causing the tote to fall.  The waste profile B155-0631 shipping description Glycol Ether Universal Waste was contained in the warehouse.  Clean up was completed 4/6/2023.  The clean up resulted in a total of 8 drums (7 -55 gallon and 1- 85 gallon).
column169: Avoid double stacking poly totes with metal cages on top of each other.  confirm if tote is in good condition.

column168: At the Toledo terminal the dockworker misjudged the position of their forks and punctured a 55-gallon plastic drum that was on a pallet being loaded in the trailer. The released material was neutralized and collected with absorbent material. The drum was placed in an overpack awaiting disposition from the shipper. We were unable to obtain identification markings on the drum due to the material being hazardous and not wanting to tamper with the material in the overpack.
column169: This incident may have been prevented had the employee been more aware of their fork position and surroundings. This employee was counselled and instructed per company policy. This incident may be used as an example in future dock training topics to show the importance of proper freight handling techniques.
